uther King, Jr.'s visit to the island in the early 1960s. Drawing on rich archival research, Milagros Denis-Rosario shows how Afro-Boricuas denounced, navigated, and negotiated racism in the fields of education, law enforcement, literature, music, the military, performance, politics, and more. Each instance of self-determination marks a gain in inclusivity—gota a gota, or drop by drop, as the saying goes in Puerto Rico. This study pays homage to them.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aBlack peoplezPuerto RicoxHistoryy20th century2DLC. 0aBlack peoplezPuerto RicoxHistoryy20th century. 0aPuerto RicansxRace identityzPuerto RicoxHistoryy20th century. 0aSocial classeszPuerto RicoxHistoryy20th century. 4aAfrican American Studies : Black Studies. 4aAmerican Studies : American Studies. 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 4aHistory : History. 4aLatin American, Caribbean, and Latinx Studies : Caribbean Studies. 7aHISTORY / Caribbean & West Indies / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2022z978311149185140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143848870740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438488707423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438488707/original  a978-3-11-149185-1  SUNY Press eBook Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles